  <h2>ADR Format</h2>
  <p>Each ADR is a Markdown file stored under <code>docs/adr/</code> in the repository and follows this template:</p>
  <pre><code># ADR-NNN: Title

**Date:** YYYY-MM-DD
**Status:** Proposed | Accepted | Deprecated | Superseded by ADR-NNN

## Context

Describe the situation that necessitated a decision. Include constraints,
requirements, and alternatives that were considered.

## Decision

State the decision that was made clearly and concisely.

## Consequences

Describe the resulting context after the decision is applied. Note both
positive outcomes and trade-offs or risks introduced.
</code></pre>

  <h2>ADR-001: Use gRPC with mTLS for Controller-Agent Communication</h2>
  <p><strong>Status:</strong> Accepted</p>
  <p><strong>Context:</strong> Agents run on remote machines, potentially across untrusted networks. The communication protocol needs to be efficient for streaming progress updates and must authenticate both ends without requiring an external identity provider.</p>
  <p><strong>Decision:</strong> Use gRPC over TLS with mutual authentication (mTLS). The Controller runs a built-in certificate authority and issues a unique certificate to each agent at enrolment time. Agents present their certificate on every connection.</p>
  <p><strong>Consequences:</strong> Strong security with no shared secrets. Certificate rotation is a manual process today; automated rotation is planned (see Roadmap). The gRPC binary framing is more efficient than REST for high-frequency progress streaming.</p>

  <h2>ADR-004: Compile the React SPA into the Controller Binary</h2>
  <p><strong>Status:</strong> Accepted</p>
  <p><strong>Context:</strong> Shipping the frontend as a separate service adds operational complexity (two processes, two containers, CORS configuration). Operators deploying on-premises value single-binary simplicity.</p>
  <p><strong>Decision:</strong> Embed the Vite-built React SPA into the Controller Go binary using <code>go:embed</code>. The Controller serves the frontend from memory on the same port as the REST API.</p>
  <p><strong>Consequences:</strong> Single binary deployment. Frontend changes require a full binary rebuild and redeploy. Acceptable for a server-side application where hot-reload is used during development only.</p>

  <h2>ADR-007: Adaptive Chunked Encoding for Parallelism</h2>
  <p><strong>Status:</strong> Accepted</p>
  <p><strong>Context:</strong> Long-form content (feature films, sports events) can take many hours to encode on a single agent. Better utilisation is achieved by splitting the source into segments and encoding them in parallel across multiple agents.</p>
  <p><strong>Decision:</strong> The Controller optionally splits a source file into N segments using scene-cut boundaries detected by PySceneDetect or fixed-interval keyframe splitting. Each segment becomes an independent task. On completion, the Controller uses ffmpeg to concatenate the outputs.</p>
  <p><strong>Consequences:</strong> Near-linear speedup proportional to agent count. Adds complexity around segment boundary alignment and audio continuity. Chunk-level retry is possible without re-encoding the entire source.</p>
